                '<strong>Define <em>amicitia</em>:</strong> Not simply "friendship" but a political relationship of mutual obligation, support, and exchange of favours. <em>Amicitia</em> was the glue of Roman political life — alliances were personal before they were ideological.',
                '<strong>Evidence from the letters:</strong> <em>Fam.</em> 5.7 to Pompey reveals the transactional nature of their relationship — Cicero seeks recognition and support in exchange for political loyalty. Letters to Atticus show the closest form of <em>amicitia</em> — genuine trust enabling frank political discussion. The contrast between what Cicero writes to different correspondents demonstrates how he maintained different political relationships simultaneously.',
                '<strong>The limits of <em>amicitia</em>:</strong> Cicero\'s letters also reveal <em>amicitia</em> breaking down under the pressure of civil war. His agonised indecision in <em>Att.</em> 8.8 partly reflects the impossibility of maintaining <em>amicitia</em> with both sides in a conflict. Pompey\'s failure to protect Cicero during his exile shows the limits of political friendship when interests diverge.',
                '<strong>Broader significance:</strong> The letters demonstrate that Roman politics operated through personal networks, not formal party structures. Understanding <em>amicitia</em> is essential for understanding why the Republic functioned — and why it collapsed when these bonds broke.'
