            evidence: '<em>Fam.</em> 5.7: transactional <em>amicitia</em> with Pompey. Letters to Atticus: intimate <em>amicitia</em> enabling honest political exchange. <em>Att.</em> 8.8: <em>amicitia</em> under strain during the civil war. The variety of Cicero\'s correspondents in the <em>ad Familiares</em> collection illustrates the network of political friendships a Roman senator maintained.',
            historiography: 'Brunt analyses <em>amicitia</em> as a political institution. Syme emphasises the role of personal factions and patronage networks in late Republican politics.'
